onomies, money lent through family and market relations, money donated with conditional cash transfers, political money that binds politicians and their supporters, sacrificed money offered to the church, and safeguarded money used to support people facing hardships. This book builds an original theory of the moral sociology of money, providing the tools for understanding the role money plays in social life today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aMoneyxMoral and ethical aspectszArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aPoorzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 4aBourdieu. 4aLatin America. 4aZelizer. 4adevelopment. 4amoney. 4amoral capital. 4amoral economy. 4aneoliberalism. 4apoor people. 4apower. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360436040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604360423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604360.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles